<p>Flights at Berlin Brandenburg Airport were suspended for almost two hours on Friday evening, October 31, after sightings of unidentified drones prompted safety measures and a temporary stop to operations . Airport operations later resumed and services returned to normal scheduling, according to local reports . The incident is one of several drone alerts around European airports and sensitive military sites in 2025, a pattern that has put airspace security under renewed scrutiny .</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/tZ26uIaxMX1yCkgqKIFk_Iz8vD9OS0acyRzXAJMJfumVHHfIqCFURqPVh3_AmJNX_xkOQxg0mDIajwqkQEJjZLzg9Od1kF3FIfaWYX2kVsJSnqduiI8UG--xtnwcOltthHWuad9E7zceTIUI9L64ufDHYo3a1hlHPJ2hqlzQLvxSofw_eH4pKTZNkglHiB5r6-o3x4VkIrWr3IR2kfY4XiAvSPTG2JsCIobYHLeJrXeriVKRiOkfp0ICeDDIeHg5N_zaJpb9-c3x' alt='A passenger walks inside Berlin Brandenburg Airport after it was closed earlier in the evening due to a drone sighting.' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>On-the-ground sighting: Officers in a patrol car visually reported seeing a drone near airport grounds but ground teams were unable to locate or recover the device, complicating immediate response efforts .</li><li>Growing trend: German officials and reporting say this episode is part of multiple 2025 incidents involving drones at airports and military sites that have heightened national security concerns .</li><li>Safety protocols: Berlin Brandenburg Airport halted flights as a precaution and cleared operations only after runway and safety checks before reopening to traffic nearly two hours later .</li><li>Passenger impact: Images from the scene show travelers moving through the terminal after the reopening, with news coverage indicating disruption but no reported injuries or mass disorder in the aftermath .</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Local police patrol officers: Officers reported a visual sighting of an unmanned aerial vehicle near airport property but were unable to locate the device on the ground . (<a href='